5000|$|Hartshorn jelly or a {{decoction}} {{of burnt}} hartshorn in water {{was used to}} treat diarrhea. The coal of hartshorn, called calcinated hartshorn, {{was used as an}} absorbent, {{as well as in the}} treatment of dysentery. Salt of hartshorn (ammonium carbonate) was used as a [...] for treatment of fevers, and as a <b>smelling</b> <b>salt.</b> Hartshorn was used to treat insect bites, sunstroke, stye, and snakebites.|$|E
50|$|Ammonium {{carbonate}} is a salt {{with the}} chemical formula (NH4)2CO3. Since it readily degrades to gaseous ammonia {{and carbon dioxide}} upon heating, it {{is used as a}} leavening agent and also as <b>smelling</b> <b>salt.</b> It is also known as baker's ammonia and was a predecessor to the more modern leavening agents baking soda and baking powder. It is a component of what was formerly known as sal volatile and salt of hartshorn.|$|E
